snippet.textDisplay:
Posted somewhere else re: Robert Downey Jr. and the Barbarian Brothers. in NATURAL BORN KILLERS.
Incredible chemistry on set - sparks flying between Iron Man and The Bruise Brothers. The Twins
were chainsaw victims of the bad guys, but happily only-from-the-waist-down. Meaning they could
still Yap (which in Peter and David's case was not always a good thing). Still marvel at the overall
profound-ness of the wise/brutal chainsaw gang. It was just screwy-enough to work. But NOT
screwy-enough to MAKE the final cut. Oliver Stone said it didn't fit - then their agents said it
didn't fit - then the city said it didn't fit - all because of just one silly reason: It doesn't and didn't fit.
...people there are parameters, I'll leave it at that.
.

snippet.textDisplay: At the beginning of this, Rogan remarks about how even though RDJ is widely seen as Tony Stark, he's able to break away and be remembered for other roles. This is why Hugh Jackman wanted to bow out of playing Wolverine -- and that was because Jerry Seinfeld had his troubles with always being known for his sitcom. Interesting. Harrison Ford was another actor that felt this way. And even with that feeling, all of these actors have managed to move onto other roles. Personally, I will always remember RDJ for his electrifying performance in The Shaggy Dog.
